            . (By interpretation.) I am warehouseman to the prosecutors, who are <rs id="t18160403-34-viclabel191" type="occupation">sugarbakers</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18160403-34-victim360 t18160403-34-viclabel191"></join>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18160403-34-victim361 t18160403-34-viclabel191"></join>. The prisoner was also in their employment. On the 1st of March, I placed myself to watch the prisoner in my house, which is by a gate on my masters' premises. I saw the prisoner come out of my master's premises at half past four in the afternoon; Miller, the officer, was with me. We immediately<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181604030031"></xptr>stopped him, and found on him four pounds of sugar, which corresponded with sugar in our warehouse, and it was double refined sugar; we found six pounds more and the candles, where he lived.</p>

